gbpservice/neutron/plugins/ml2plus/drive.message: Given that we have to stop this in the UTs, are we sure that we don't need to stop this somewhere in the class?

The ApicAimTestCase.setUp() method has code that replaces the NovaClient.get_servers() method with a mock, in order to prevent repeated exceptions from this LoopingCall thread since there is no nova server. But it seems to me that a new LoopingCall thread is being launched for each UT that is run, which would be extremely wasteful. 

Neutron doesn't have any general shutdown mechanism for the plugin and drivers that would cause them to cleanup when the server is being shutdown, so it's not realistic to expect these LoopingCall threads to be stopped by normal plugin/driver code during UTs. We could add something to ApicAimTestCase.tearDown() that stops the LoopingCall thread.

Maybe it would be best to replace the patching of NovaClient.get_servers() in ApicAimTestCase.setUp() with patching of this _setup_nova_vm_update() method so that no LoopingCall thread is launched during plugin initialization during most unit tests. Then the specific UTs for the vm update could call the real _setup_nova_vm_update method to launch the LoopingCall thread, and then stop the thread afterwards.

I was following neutron upstream code to set up this looping thread,
https://github.com/openstack/neutron/blob/master/neutron/agent/dhcp/agent.py#L845-L848
As you can see there, they also don't do any special cleanup. 
I think when neutron-server process is being terminated, all the threads will be gone also. And I've verified that on a fab. 

I can follow Bob's suggestion to add another mock for _setup_nova_vm_update() during the setUp() phase. I will still need the mock for NovaClient.get_servers() though because I will need that in another UT test_update_nova_vm_name_cache().

gbpservice/neutron/tests/unit/plugins/ml.message: Not that it's likely, but if this UT were to fail in any of the asserts above, the mock would remain in place for subsequent tests run by the process. It would be better to use the mock.patch() context manager to install the patched function, as it will undo the patch when exiting the with clause, regardless of how it is exited.

Save this in the UT class, not the driver class:

    self.orig_setup_nova_vm_update = self.driver._setup_nova_vm_update

This change does not have the intended effect of preventing hundreds of unnecessary LoopingCall threads from being launched during a UT run, which make many thousands of _update_nova_vm
_name_cache calls. This is because _setup_nova_vm_update gets called by ApicMechanismDriver.initialize when this class's base class's setUp method is called on line 322 above, before this patch has been installed.

You need to move this patching before the base class setUp call. Because the plugin and driver have not yet been initialized at that point, you'll also need to change this to patch the class rather than the instance.

Finally, you will need to remove the patching of the class, probably in the tearDown function, so that the next UT run in the same process does not save the mock function from the previous run instead of the real function.

ok make sense. I can move up the patch then. But I don't think  I can do this any more since self.driver hasn't been set up yet,
self.orig_setup_nova_vm_update = self.driver._setup_nova_vm_update
Will have to see what I can do there then.

Use this from the UT class:

    self.orig_setup_nova_vm_update()
This change does seem to resolve the issue with constant stack traces during the remainder of the UT run.

I think this should be swift-account-*server* -- if we make that change instead, this list of services makes a bit more sense:

* We run one account-server using /etc/swift/account-server/account-server.conf; it'll listen to an ip/port that the proxy-server can talk to in order to handle client traffic.
* If a dedicated replication network is configured, we run another account-server using /etc/swift/account-server/account-server-replicator.conf to listen on the replication network. The account-replicators will talk to that server, with (hopefully) minimal impact on client-facing traffic.
* If there's no dedicated replication network, the account-server handling client traffic will handle replication traffic as well.

I'm not sure I understand this change to grenade. I've double checked with the devstack-gate grenade driver and I believe it triggers grenade.sh on the primary node to do both the old and new sides of things.

That said it did farm out the old subnode install to devstack since the way grenade multinode jobs are set up is to only upgrade the primary and leave the old subnode in place to ensure old compute/etc can work with new controller code.

I don't think this is necessarily wrong but it might help to explain why this choice was made for the zuulv3 version. Maybe a comment here?

The idea is to reduce the duplication. We already have a proven method for driving devstack, which is made by the roles defined inside devstack.git. So we can just use it.

I suspect that going forward we could reduce grenade.sh just to the upgrade part. Separation of concerns, less clutter around.

heat/objects/resource.py.message: I certainly like the theory, but please can you clarify what these units are?  If that's a potential of 60 seconds that's very high to be stuck.

yes, these are seconds. from the tenacity docs

  Randomly wait up to 2^x * <multiplier> seconds between each retry until the range reaches <max> seconds, then randomly up to <max> seconds afterwards

so the wait is only potentially max 60 seconds, it is a random number up to 60.

The progression of stuck time would be
1. random from 0 to 1 second
2. random from 0 to 2 seconds
3. random from 0 to 4 seconds
4. random from 0 to 8 seconds
5. random from 0 to 16 seconds
6. random from 0 to 32 seconds
7..11. random from 0 to 60 seconds

We have observed that in a (may be not very optimally written) stack were same resource was used from ~30 other resources, so that the hardcoded defaults here (11 retries up to 2 seconds sleep) were still not enough (so at least one of those went to error due to conflict).

What would you think be an appropriate cut-off for this?
(Ideally configurable may be...)?

roles/build-test-packages/tasks/main.yml.message:
Using the stat module is a pretty heavy way to go about it - it does a checksum and all sorts of other stuff. The find module with a regex would be faster.

However, this could all be done in a single task which will execute faster if done with a shell script, something like:

  - name: Clean up loop devices created by mock
    shell: |-
      exit_code=0
      for d in $(find /dev -maxdepth 1 -regex '/dev/loop[0-9]+'); do
        rm -f ${d}
        exit_code=2
      done
      exit ${exit_code}
    register: _loop_cleanup
    changed_when: _loop_cleanup.rc == 2
    failed_when: _loop_cleanup.rc not in [0,2]

was a bit concerned about the hard-coding here... 

i see it defaults to that in mock https://github.com/rpm-software-management/mock/blob/42df0034f0046fb84f989af83a9d2f2aa7085901/mock/py/mockbuild/util.py#L1229

we don't want to delete all the loop devices, want to persist loop devices which were created outside of mock, so doesn't seem it will work just with single task.

yes agree when going with stat it will take couple of more seconds but seems more cleaner than adding a shell script. Yes can try find module instead of stat if that helps?
